  "created": "2025-10-15",
  "description": "DNA replication elongation in E. coli is performed by the highly processive DNA polymerase III holoenzyme. The replisome complex coordinates synthesis on both leading and lagging strands simultaneously, with the leading strand synthesized continuously and the lagging strand synthesized discontinuously as Okazaki fragments. The process involves continuous proofreading by the 3'-5' exonuclease activity, processivity enhancement by the beta clamp (dnaN), and coordination between helicase (DnaB), primase (DnaG), and polymerase activities. This flowchart illustrates the complete elongation process including strand-specific synthesis mechanisms, Okazaki fragment processing, proofreading, and the coupling of leading and lagging strand synthesis.",
  "id": "ecoli_dna_replication_elongation",
  "keywords": [
    "dna replication",
    "dna polymerase iii",
    "replisome",
    "leading strand",
    "lagging strand",
    "okazaki fragments",
    "proofreading",
    "processivity",
    "beta clamp",
    "helicase"
  ],
